snippet.textDisplay:
He’s a gift. So many people fake it all of their lives, or just self-medicate, running from the emptiness they feel inside. I don’t think Justin can fake it. He is who he is and can’t hide it. And that’s a precious gift to all the young folks who are convinced that popularity and fame equals happiness. He refuses to numb himself out again (which temporarily looks better) and has decided to face hard stuff, which, yeah, looks pretty bad at first.
Keep going Justin. Keep surrounding yourself with great people who are not flattered by you, but those who truly love you as they love God. God is going to replace anxiety with assurance as you keep on going on with Him.

snippet.textDisplay: This was a really impressive interview/conversation and humble connections made by both.   Both Zane and Justin were very genuine, sincere and touched on very applicable, deep subject matter.  Both have a good grasp of decency and intelligence.  Being in the present.  So proud to see a fellow Kiwi/New Zealander/professional, interact with a major artist with such class, consideration, sincerity and genuine care/hospitality.  As Kiwi's, we are grounded and people are most important above status, in our Maori culture especially.  I would say that was felt and evident in this exchange and created a good energy flow for Justin just to be 'Justin the person' over the artist and be open to share.  It was lovely to see the healing influence of making real (spiritual) connections between two human beings exchanging, truely listening and sharing one with another about life, love, pain, struggles and triumphs etc.  This was something that you could feel above just viewing.

snippet.textDisplay: There is alot of truth in "cry me a river in your Rolls-Royce" normal people cant relate to masses of people yelling your name, girls lining up the block to sleep with you, more money than you know what to do with, cameras in your face 24/7 and though the story of his struggles might be interesting the average person cant see past the superficial public persona of Justin Bieber.  He and I might have similar issues with drugs, faith, marriage, friendships, career but that's where the similarities end. The normal person has the same issues with stresses on top that Justin Bieber has never had to deal with, if he is going through something that's affecting his life or work he can take off for 3 years and still buy a 9 million dollar mansion and travel the world to work through his shit. If the average person has that issue we can't take off, we can't go on vacation, we have to deal with those issues while we work so that we can pay the rent, electric bill, groceries and it's a very real thing that you might not be able to do any of those if you don't work for a week or two weeks.  So while I feel for him and his issues, when I look at him and see him talking I can only think "I hate that for ya but i'm going through that to and i've missed 4 days of work and now i'm dealing with that plus worrying like hell how i'm gonna pay rent" but I've also never had to wonder if a friend was a friend or simply in my life because of my fame or there because of my wealth so there are definitely aspects of his struggles I don't have. It's easy to look in and say he's entitled and does not have "real" problems but the truth is we all as a species deal with similar issues and life events and illnesses and though we can't all always relate at a particular time it doesn't mean that his issues aren't causing him just as much pain and suffering as yours.

snippet.textDisplay:
Really hope he can pick himself up and learn to love life again. I've been similarly blessed with natural talent, empathy, intelligence plus creativity and people come to expect a lot from you. I can't even image how overwhelming it must be to be on Justins level. Creatives just want space to create but he's been trapped in a box and bombarded by fans + media.

Having been through similar tough times in my early 20's I just have one thing to say: Please keep spreading love and good music JB. You have such a positive impact on so many people and that in itself gives you such an undeniable purpose to be part of this world.

Much love <3 keep on writing, singing and spreading compassion/ positivity. Keep looking up and moving forwards! Jonny from Ldn x

snippet.textDisplay: This is the most wholesome and honest interview/talk I’ve seen and I have teared up a few times. I don’t know if you’ll see my comment, or if it will matter.. but I am so proud of you for growing, for being so open and honest and helping those of us that deal with mental health issues see that it’s not just us. That even the “famous” people have hardships and not to judge anyone harshly. I honestly got very emotional. Keep up the good work. One day at a time. You are a powerhouse Justin, and I’m glad you found someone you can share a beautiful life with. Through hardships and the most beautiful times. Stick on this path of healing. You’re going to make it. All my love, for both you and Hailey. God Bless.
